The glucose-dependent insulinotropic polypeptide signaling axis in the central nervous 
system 
 
Authors:  
A.E. Adriaenssens1, F.M. Gribble1*, F. Reimann1* 
 
1 Metabolic Research Laboratories, Wellcome Trust MRC Institute of Metabolic Science, 
Addenbrooke‘s Hospital, Hills Road, Cambridge, CB2 0QQ, UK 
* Joint corresponding authors 
*Correspondence to: fmg23@cam.ac.uk or fr222@cam.ac.uk  
 
Highlights 
Glucose-dependent insulinotropic polypeptide receptor (GIPR) is expressed in feeding centres 
GIPR+ cell activation inhibits food intake, yet inhibiting GIPR enhances leptin’s anorexic effect 
GIPR+ cells also play a role in memory formation and learning 
 
Abstract: 
 
 
 
Glucose-dependent insulinotropic polypeptide (GIP) is an incretin hormone released 
from the epithelium of the upper small intestine. While GIP shares common actions on the 
pancreatic beta cell with glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1), unlike GLP-1, GIP presents a 
complex target for the development of diabetes and obesity therapies due to its extra-
pancreatic effects on fat mass. Recent pharmacological developments, however, have 
provided insight into a previously unrecognized role for GIP receptor (GIPR) signaling in 
regulating appetite. Additionally, GIP-based therapeutics have demonstrated promising 
neuroprotective properties. Together these observations identify an important central 
component of the GIP/GIPR signaling axis, and have triggered a resurgence of research 
interest into the central actions of GIP. In this review, we discuss what is currently known 
about where GIP may act in the central nervous system (CNS), the characteristics of its target 
cell populations, and the physiological effects of manipulating the activity Gipr-expressing 
cells in the brain.  
 
Key Words: 
 
Glucose-dependent insulinotropic polypeptide 
Glucose-dependent insulinotropic polypeptide receptor 
Central nervous system 
 
 
 
Journal Pre-proof
2 
 
Introduction: 
 
Glucose-dependent insulinotropic polypeptide (GIP), synthesized and released from 
enteroendocrine cells lining the intestinal epithelium [1], belongs to the secretin/glucagon 
family of structurally related peptides that includes secretin, glucagon, GLP-1, GLP-2, 
growth hormone-releasing factor (GHRF), peptide histidine-methionine (PHM), vasoactive 
intestinal polypeptide (VIP) and pituitary adenylyl cyclase-activating polypeptide (PACAP). 
Many members of the secretin/glucagon peptide family, including VIP, PACAP, secretin, and 
GLP-1, are accepted neurotransmitters, and are known to be distributed widely throughout 
the central nervous system (CNS) and their central actions range from the regulation of food 
intake and body temperature, to brain development and cell-cycle regulation [2]. Until 
recently, interest in a possible role for GIP as a central regulatory peptide has been eclipsed 
by intense effort paid to other members of the secretin/glucagon family, such as GLP-1. 
Instead, more research focus has been given to understanding GIP’s peripheral effects, 
especially its apparent adipogenic properties.  
Recently, however, the advent of novel therapeutics targeting the GIP signaling axis 
has reinvigorated the field’s interest in GIP’s possible actions in the brain. These drugs are 
the GIP receptor (GIPR) antagonists, and the GIPR and GLP-1 receptor (GLP1R) dual 
agonists. These drug classes have demonstrated that GIPR signaling presents a novel target 
for the regulation of energy homeostasis, and, for the first time, place GIP amongst other gut 
peptides known to mediate the gut-brain axis. Outside of regulating energy balance, GIP-
based therapies have also shown promise in alleviating neurological symptoms associated 
with dementia-related diseases. Although a general understanding of GIP’s diverse actions 
within the brain is beginning to take shape, much work needs to be done to determine how to 
modulate GIP and GIPR activity to the best therapeutic advantage.   
Here we discuss what is currently known about the role of GIPR signaling in the 
CNS, including Gipr localization, the characterization of the cell types expressing Gipr, and 
the role of GIPR signaling and target cell activation in vivo.  
 
Gipr CNS localization 
 
First indications that GIP could play a regulatory role in the brain came from 
experiments demonstrating that ventricular administration of GIP inhibits FSH secretion, 
leading the authors to believe that GIP could act on the hypothalamus via the median 
eminence or other circumventricular structures to affect pituitary hormone release [3]. 
Evidence confirming the presence of GIPR in the brain, however, didn’t come for nearly 
another decade, when the sequence for Gipr was uncovered.  
Gipr was first cloned and sequenced from a rat cerebral cortex cDNA library [4], and 
was found to be highly conserved across species as a member of the VIP/glucagon/secretin 
receptor family of G protein-coupled receptors  [5, 6]. In addition to being expressed in the 
cerebral cortex, Gipr mRNA was also initially found in the hippocampus, olfactory bulb, 
mammillary bodies, brain stem, and cerebellum in rats [4]. Early efforts to build a 
neuroanatomical atlas of functional GIPR ligand binding activity used [125I]GIP in 
autoradiographic analysis. In slices of rat brain, [125I]GIP binding was observed in several 
cortical areas, the anterior olfactory nucleus, lateral septum, subiculum, inferior colliculus, 
brain stem, and the inferior olive [7]. Widespread expression of Gipr in the adult mouse brain 
has since been confirmed by in situ hybridization [8], and qPCR [9-11]. While studies 
locating Gipr in the CNS using traditional in situ hybridisation and radiolabelled ligands  or 
qPCR have provided critical insight into brain regions that may mediate GIP-dependent 
actions, the low resolution of these methodologies does not allow for the precise mapping of 
Journal Pre-proof
3 
 
Gipr production to discrete cell populations, and though antibodies against GIPR have been 
designed as functional antagonists, these have not been used for the specific 
immunohistochemical visualization of GIPR in tissue.  
In a recent study, an alternative strategy for characterizing regions and cell types 
important for GIP signaling in the CNS was used. Knock-in transgenic mice were designed 
replacing one copy of the Gipr coding sequence with that encoding Cre recombinase (Gipr-
Cre) [12]. Upon crossing Gipr-Cre mice with a ROSA26-EYFP reporter strain, EYFP is 
expressed in cells transcribing Gipr, allowing for the detection of Gipr expression via 
immunostaining for EYFP using specific, validated antibodies. This fluorescent reporter 
approach not only allows for the localization of Gipr expression to discrete cells, but it also 
facilitates the detection of Gipr in cells where Gipr expression levels are low due to the 
relative signal amplification offered by the ROSA26-driven transcription of EYFP, thereby 
enabling higher resolution mapping of Gipr expression in the CNS. Similar to in situ and 
radiolabelling mapping, Gipr expression was confirmed in the olfactory bulb, cortical layers, 
and hippocampus in Gipr-Cre mice. Gipr expression was additionally found in the medial 
preoptic area, subfornical organ, anterodorsal thalamic nucleus, paraventricular thalamic 
nucleus, magnocellular preoptic nucleus, suprachiasmatic nucleus, and the interfascicular 
nucleus. Of note, Gipr expression was also detected in the paraventricular, dorsomedial, and 
arcuate nuclei of the hypothalamus and the area postrema—the latter being another important 
circumventricular region densely vascularized and integral to the communication of 
peripheral signals to nearby areas like the nucleus of the solitary tract (NTS), which is known 
to be critical in mediating the central effects of gut peptides. While Gipr expression in the 
hypothalamus has not been previously reported in earlier mapping studies, transcription of 
Gipr was confirmed by qPCR in whole hypothalamic homogenates isolated from mice [9, 11, 
12] and non-human primates [13]. Additionally, single molecule in situ hybridization 
(smISH) experiments confirmed the presence of Gipr in the dorsomedial and arcuate nuclei 
of the mouse, as well as the paraventricular and dorsomedial nuclei and the mediobasal and 
lateral hypothalamus in humans [12], indicating that GIPR signaling could engage neural 
networks critical for the regulation of energy homeostasis across species. 
Interestingly, when comparing Gipr- to Glp1r-expressing regions in the brain, there 
are a number of areas where incretin receptors appear to overlap, potentially indicating 
related central actions. Specifically, Glp1r is also found in cortical regions, hippocampus, 
preoptic area, thalamic nuclei, subfornical organ, area postrema, and the hypothalamus [14]. 
At the transcript level, both Gipr and Glp1r are detected in hypothalamic isolates from mice 
[12] and non-human primates [13], and in both mouse and human hypothalamus smISH 
analysis revealed expression of Gipr and Glp1r in distinct as well as overlapping cell 
populations. Human hypothalamic tissue exhibited a higher proportion of Gipr-positive cells 
that also expressed Glp1r [12]. Future studies are needed to address whether there could be 
species differences with respect to how GIP and GLP-1 signaling pathways converge in this 
brain region.  
 
Gipr cell type characterization via transcriptomics 
 
Single-cell RNA sequencing (scRNAseq) performed in Gipr-positive cells from the 
hypothalamus revealed their substantial heterogeneity. Markers for neurons, glia, and 
vascular cells demarcated different subpopulations of hypothalamic Gipr cells [12]. Within 
the neuronal subpopulation, Gipr cells co-expressed genes encoding the neurohormones Sst, 
Avp, Tac1, and Cartpt. Gipr neurons also expressed receptors for other gut peptides, 
including ghrelin and CCK, indicating that these cells are equipped to be regulated by signals 
from the periphery. Indeed, calcium imaging analysis confirmed that agonism of these 
Journal Pre-proof
4 
 
receptors results in Gipr cell excitation [12]. The wide range of different cell types expressing 
Gipr suggests that GIP has pleiotropic effects on the CNS, a possibility that should remain a 
research priority in coming years.  
 
Gip expression in the brain 
 
The identification of Gipr in the CNS, especially in brain regions protected by the 
blood brain barrier, raises key questions surrounding the physiological role of GIPR signaling 
in the brain. In particular, it is important to know the source of GIP, and whether GIPR in the 
CNS responds to circulating levels of the gut peptide or whether GIP may be produced 
centrally. Evidence for GIP peptide secretion in the brain is mixed. Early studies reported that 
Gip mRNA could not be detected by RNA blot hybridization in isolates from rat cerebrum, 
hypothalamus, or cerebellum [15], or by RT-PCR [4]. More recent studies have since 
reported detectable levels of Gip mRNA in rat hippocampus, thalamus, cerebellum, 
brainstem, and cortex, with in situ hybridization reporting weak Gip signals in the granule 
cell layer and CA1-CA3 region of the hippocampus [16, 17]. While immunohistochemical 
analysis for GIP in rat tissue found positive staining in several brain regions, results from 
concurrent RT-PCR analysis were not in agreement [17], perhaps owing to very low 
expression levels of Gip as measured by qRT-PCR in brain samples [10, 16] or potential 
cross-reactivity of the antibody with other secretin family members, although this has been 
ruled out for glucagon [18]. Attempts by our group to locate Gip-expressing cells in the brain 
via transgenic labelling failed to detect fluorescent signal in serially sectioned mouse brains 
of GIP-Cre x EYFP mice (unpublished data) – however, even in the upper small intestine 
where Gip expression is high, this mouse model labels only ~60% of cells stained for GIP 
[19], raising the possibility that Gip-expressing neurons could also fail detection by this 
method. Whether GIP is a centrally-produced regulator of brain function is thus still up for 
debate. Peripherally-secreted GIP, however, may modulate central processes as part of the 
gut-brain axis and supporting this idea, i.p. injected GIP has been reported to raise GIP levels 
in CSF drained from the cisterna magna in mice [10]. 
 
Central GIPR signaling in body weight regulation 
 
Reports on the role of GIP and GIPR signaling in body weight regulation have made 
GIPR a confusing target for anti-obesity therapeutics. In a study that prompted a refocusing 
of the incretin field back onto GIP, Miyawaki et al demonstrated that Gipr knock-out mice 
are protected against diet-induced obesity [20]. Following from this work, a suite of strategies 
aimed at neutralizing GIP signaling have been designed in an effort to create novel 
therapeutics for the treatment of obesity [10, 21, 22]. Perplexingly, while GIPR antagonism 
results in body weight loss, so does GIPR agonsim, particularly when combined with GLP-1 
analogues [23-27], reviewed in [28, 29]. In rodents and humans, augmenting GIPR signaling 
in combination with GLP-1 agonism significantly improved glycaemic control and provided 
greater body weight loss compared to treatment with a GLP-1 receptor agonist alone [23, 24, 
26, 27], and in mice, this additional weight loss could be attributable to a further reduction in 
food intake [23, 24, 27]. 
To date it is still unclear exactly which signaling mechanisms underlie changes in 
body weight elicited by GIPR agonists or antagonists. As Gipr is expressed in the periphery 
as well as the CNS, a key question to address is whether GIPR antagonists and agonists differ 
in their primary target tissues. It is likely that the resistance to weight gain exhibited by Gipr 
knock-out mice, is at least in part due to altered insulin release due to islet beta cell 
adaptation [30] and GIPR signaling in adipose tissue [31]. Indeed Glp1r knock-out mice, 
Journal Pre-proof
5 
 
which also exhibit an impaired incretin response, are similarly protected against diet-induced 
obesity [32, 33]. Antagonistic antibodies are unlikely to cross the blood brain barrier (BBB), 
and as a result perhaps principally elicit their effects through actions in peripheral tissues 
[21]. In contrast, peptide-based therapeutics are potentially capable of crossing the BBB. The 
weight loss demonstrated by peptide GIPR and GIPR/GLP1R dual agonists corresponds with 
a reduction in food intake [23, 24, 27], strongly implicating the CNS as their target tissue, 
and, in the case of dual agonists, suggests that added GIPR activation may act to sensitize 
appetitive pathways in the brain to GLP-1, an established anorectic signal.  
The finding that Gipr cells are present in the ARC, DMH and PVH is congruent with 
GIPR signaling integrating with well-characterized hypothalamic circuits regulating energy 
balance [34]. Transcriptomic analysis revealed that Gipr neurons in the hypothalamus also 
express established anorectic neuropeptides, in particular Avp and Cartpt [35], [36], which 
were found in over 40% of Gipr neurons [12]. Compatible with the anorexia induced by 
GIPR and GIPR/GLP1R dual agonists, chemogenic activation of hypothalamic Gipr cells 
resulted in an acute reduction in food intake [12], highlighting the potential of cells targeted 
by GIP in the CNS to alter feeding behavior. 
Kaneko and colleagues have recently linked native GIPR signaling to leptin sensitivity in 
the hypothalamus. Genetic or pharmacological blockade of GIPR enhanced the anorexigenic 
effects of leptin in mice fed a high fat diet—conditions usually resulting in the development 
of leptin resistance—leading the authors to propose that GIPR signaling inhibits leptin-
mediated anorexia [10]. GIPR activation triggers cAMP-dependent pathways that engage 
protein kinase A (PKA) and exchange protein directly activated by cAMP (EPAC) signaling 
cascades. Mice null for Rap1, a downstream target of EPAC, were protected against GIP-
induced leptin resistance, supporting a model where elevated circulating GIP levels stimulate 
GIPR, leading to EPAC-mediated Rap1 activation and resulting leptin resistance [10, 37]. 
These data are not necessarily mutually exclusive with chemogenetic experiments in Gipr-
Cre mice [12], as both studies identify an anorexigenic Gipr-expressing cell population in the 
hypothalamus that may also be a target for leptin signaling [12]. A conundrum remains, 
however, regarding the fact that both GIPR agonists and antagonists are capable of reducing 
body weight through food intake. The mechanistic detail describing how each drug class 
engages GIPR signaling and its target cells in the brain will be a critical step in refining these 
potential anti-obesity therapies, and presents an important and exciting subject for future 
research. 
 
Central GIPR and the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis 
 
 
The expression of Gipr in the PVN [12] and pituitary [11] could implicate GIP in 
regulating body weight through the HPA axis. Elevated levels of glucocorticoid hormones 
promote obesity and metabolic syndrome [38, 39]. While Gipr is not expressed in healthy 
human adrenal gland tissue, some patients suffering from “food-dependent” Cushing’s 
syndrome exhibit ectopic expression of Gipr on the surface of adrenal tumors, potentially 
contributing to postprandial hypersecretion of cortisol and subsequent weight gain [40]. This 
has led to the hypothesis that the antagonism of GIPR may protect against GIP-mediated 
glucocorticoid release post-nutrient ingestion [11]. In rodents, where Gipr is expressed in the 
adrenal cortex of healthy animals [41], however, supplementation of corticosterone in Gipr 
knock out animals subjected to a high fat diet did not affect body weight [11], perhaps 
suggesting that GIP’s effects on body weight are not primarily mediated via the HPA axis.     
 
 
Central GIPR signaling in neurogenesis, memory, and learning 
Journal Pre-proof
6 
 
 
In agreement with GIP’s anti-apoptotic role in pancreatic beta cells, osteoblasts, and 
vascular endothelial cells [42, 43], GIPR signaling may also promote cellular survival and 
regenerative capacity in the nervous system. Following ICV administration, GIP increased 
hippocampal progenitor cell proliferation [16]. In vitro, this proliferative effect was shown to 
be dependent on intact GIPR signaling [16]. Mice vaccinated against endogenous GIP 
exhibited an increase in hippocampal cell apoptosis that correlated with decreased glucose 
utilization as measured by 18F-FDG/PET scan [44]. Similarly, in the granule cell layer of the 
dentate gyrus, GIPR knock-out mice had lower numbers of BrdU-positive cells compared to 
control mice, indicating compromised cell proliferation. Decreased hippocampal cell 
proliferation in GIPR knock-out mice however did not seem to affect the number of immature 
neurons found in this region [45], suggesting that although Gipr may play a role in regulating 
progenitor cell proliferation, it is not involved in neuronal differentiation. The hippocampus 
is important for recent memory formation and orientation processes. Thus, confirmed Gipr 
expression in this region suggests that Gipr signalling may be important in cognitive 
processes including memory, spatial recognition and coordination, and learning.Accordingly, 
a study by Faivre et al demonstrated that Gipr knock-out mice are cognitivelyimpaired: Gipr 
knock-out mice failed to discriminate between novel and familiar objects,indicating that 
intact GIPR signalling affects memory task performance [45]. Intact GIPRsignalling also 
promotes spatial learning and memory, as Gipr knock-out mice struggled tolocate escape 
platforms in a Morris water maze trial compared to WT controls—data which 
arecorroborated by experiments showing that exercise-induced increases in hippocampal 
Giprexpression correlated with better special memory performance in the same Morris water 
mazetask [46]. Similarly, GIP over-expressing mice exhibited improved performance in a Y-
maze test [47], though this may be related to the increased overall activity observed in these 
mice.  
Memory formation is driven by the strengthening of synaptic communication between 
neurons. GIPR signaling in the hippocampus may regulate the electrophysiological 
underpinnings of synaptic plasticity and memory development, as acute ICV administration 
of GIP promoted long term potentiation (LTP) [48]. In the area CA1 of the hippocampus, 
GIPR agonism enhanced [48], whereas genetic deletion of Gipr impaired, LTP induction 
[45], an effect postulated to involve the modulation of vesicle release at the presynaptic site 
[48]. GIPR agonist-mediated promotion of LTP correlates with amelioration of the damaging 
effects of physiological stressors, such as high-fat feeding, on learning and memory tasks [49, 
50], though it is unclear whether the observed cognitive improvement is a direct effect of 
GIPR activation or whether it is due to improved metabolic control. 
GIP’s implied cognitive role combined with evidence suggesting that hyperglycemia 
and insulin resistance could play a role in the development of dementia-related disease [51], 
has led some groups to believe that GIP analogues may represent potential therapeutic 
strategies for neurodegenerative disorders. The stable GIP analog, D-Ala(2)GIP, preserved 
synaptic plasticity, reduced amyloid plaque load, and prevented signs of inflammation and 
oxidative stress in cortical tissue in a rodent model of Alzheimer’s disease. In a chronic 
Parkinson’s disease model, GIPR agonism prevented the loss of dopaminergic neurons in the 
substantia nigra pars compacta and prevented motor dysfunction while simultaneously 
decreasing the expression of a-synuclein [52]. Treatment with D-Ala(2)GIP also improved 
locomotor activity, neuromuscular coordination, and short-term episodic memory in a rodent 
model of Huntington’s disease, potentially through decreasing lipid peroxidation and 
restoring antioxidant and monoamine levels in the brain [53]. Similar to the improved 
glycemic and weight reducing performance of combinatorial incretin therapies, drugs 
incorporating both GIPR and GLP1R agonist activity have also exhibited enhanced reversal 
Journal Pre-proof
7 
 
of neurological symptoms associated with Alzheimer’s disease compared to monotherapy 
[54]. Though the neurocognitive potential of GIPR agonism is yet to be established in 
humans, the future of GIP-based mono and combinatorial therapies in the field of 
neurodegenerative diseases appears bright, and is a topic further discussed elsewhere in this 
issue. 
 
Conclusion  
 
Due to innovative pharmacology, the incretin field is starting to reevaluate the GIPR 
signaling axis, seeing GIP now as an important therapeutic target rather than simply the sister 
incretin to GLP-1. In particular it has become increasingly apparent that GIPR and its 
downstream signaling is a critical modulator of energy balance and cognitive health, roles 
partially mediated by GIPR present in the CNS (Figure 1). Though we are starting to build a 
picture of the identity and function of central target cells for GIP, in order to better leverage 
the potential therapeutic benefits of GIPR, more work is needed to understand how Gipr-
expressing cells in the brain integrate with homeostatic pathways. With divergent strategies 
for the manipulation of GIPR physiology revealing key putative actions of GIP in the brain, 
untangling GIPR signaling in the CNS promises to be an exciting area of exploration.   
 
