Figure Legends: 
 
Figure 1: Role of GIPR signaling in the CNS. GIP produced by enteroendocrine cells 
lining the small intestine is secreted into the bloodstream. Central GIPR activation regulates 
both cognitive processes and appetite regulation. In the hippocampus, GIP promotes synaptic 
plasticity and progenitor cell proliferation, actions thought to contribute to neuroprotection, 
learning, and memory formation. In the hypothalamus, activation of Gipr-expressing cells 
decreases food intake. The exact mechanism underlying this activation remains unclear. 
GIPR agonism may directly excite anorexigenic neurons, or could trigger GIP-dependent 
sensitization of neurons to other anorectic stimuli such as GLP-1. Alternatively, GIPR 
antagonism could alleviate leptin resistance, permitting leptin receptor-mediated suppression 
of appetite. GIP, glucose-dependent insulinotropic polypeptide; GIPR, glucose-dependent 
insulinotropic polypeptide receptor; GLP-1, glucagon-like peptide-1; GLP1R, glucagon-like 
peptide-1 receptor; EPAC, exchange protein directly activated by cAMP; LEPR, leptin 
receptor   
 
 
